{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: classifier request-construction plus API-client dispatch payload. A pure Unit test on a helper could miss dropped/overwritten labels between modules (MOCK-MISS). Real network/OS is not required because an in-process fake client can capture the exact outbound payload (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a=false). Correctness does not depend on model judgment (b=false) and no multi-agent chain exists (c/d=false). Rejected System because behavior text is about request contents, not real HTTP/network effects.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a fake in-process API client that records outbound requests. Invoke classify with a known taxonomy and assert the sent payload contains every taxonomy label exactly as configured.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is local validation/normalization logic on returned label. No required cross-module interaction to expose it (MOCK-MISS). No OS/network/subprocess dependency (REAL-INFRA no). No dependence on real model quality; input can be a fixed raw label string (LLM-DEP no). Rejected Integration because behavior text is strictly output-mapping rule: \"returns 'unknown' instead of forwarding\".","test_description":"Call the normalization/decision function with taxonomy {legal, technical, financial, other} and raw label 'medical'; assert final label is 'unknown'.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.15,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior explicitly scopes to normalization determinism for identical raw inputs, which is local function behavior. No module boundary or real infra required. Rejected higher levels because text disqualifies them: \"identical raw API responses\" isolates post-response normalization only.","test_description":"Feed the same raw response object/string multiple times into normalization and assert identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.05,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency relative to provider response variation. A stub cannot reveal real-model/provider variability, so mocks can hide failures (MOCK-HIDE). This is not just transport infrastructure; correctness depends on real model/provider outputs over runs (LLM-DEP yes). Rejected Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-agent staged pipeline.","test_description":"Run N repeated real classification calls for the same document+taxonomy, capture raw provider outputs and final labels, and assert final-label changes occur only when raw provider response changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at boundary between tokenizer/budget policy and dispatcher: budget may be computed but not enforced before send (MOCK-MISS). In-process fakes can detect whether dispatch happened and what payload length/tokens were sent. Real OS/network not required (a=false). No dependence on model output quality (b=false). Rejected Unit because behavior text includes \"before dispatch,\" a cross-module handoff condition.","test_description":"Use real request-construction path with fake tokenizer/config and fake API client. Provide over-budget input; assert policy action (truncate or reject) occurs and outbound dispatch reflects enforced budget (or is blocked).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Needs real provider-reported usage; local token estimators/mocks can systematically miss provider tokenization/accounting behavior (MOCK-HIDE). This executes a real AI API call and assertion depends on actual model-service usage metadata, so Agentic is the safer minimum per LLM-DEP rule. Rejected Integration because behavior text explicitly requires \"Provider-reported token usage.\" Rejected Workflow because only one model call step is required.","test_description":"Send representative documents to the real provider through the module, read usage metadata returned by provider, and assert reported prompt/total tokens are <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is retry orchestration across modules (error handling, backoff/wait, re-dispatch). This is catchable with in-process fake API returning rate-limit then success; no real network/OS primitive is required for minimum failure detection. Behavior does not depend on model output content (LLM-DEP no). Rejected System because text is protocol-level signal handling, not real network timing pathology.","test_description":"Wire classifier to fake API client scripted to return rate-limit error then success; use controllable clock/sleeper; assert module waits per retry policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of surfacing error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
